pr_title: modals: Remove `in` class once modal is hidden.
pr_body:
Rapdly clicking a button that shows a modal cause a race condition
in Bootstrap. Specifically, Bootstrap adds an "in" class to a modal
on the "shown" event and removes it on the "hide" event. Frequent clicks
cause the "hide" event to trigger before the "shown" event. Therefore, the
"in" class isn't removed. We use the "in" class to check if a modal is
active in overlays.js

For now, we manually remove it once the modal is hidden.

So, I just noticed that we use Bootstrap 2 which is like super old.
Newer versions of Bootstrap probably handle this better internally.
Look into removing this once it's upgraded.

For instance, Bootstrap 4 handles rapid clicks better (Demo: https://jsfiddle.net/q256fysj/1/) while Bootstrap 2 doesn't do it so well (Demo: https://jsfiddle.net/3et8ab0x/1/).

So, I think upgrading Bootstrap will fix this naturally.

### Before

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/58626718/120934948-2a721d00-c71e-11eb-88c9-f6b488ce8ae1.mp4

### After (I am clicking rapidly here)
https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/58626718/120934970-41b10a80-c71e-11eb-9ab8-dbbde6c77fc5.mp4

### Similarly

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/58626718/120935010-6c02c800-c71e-11eb-95a6-a8a80bba0c96.mp4

pr_title: user_deactivation: Move modal_parent one level up in confirm_dialog.
pr_body:
The user deactivate button is also present in the "Deactivated users"
tab, a sibling element of the current modal_parent, #admin-user-list.
Adding the confirm_dialog modal to #admin-user-list won't have any
effect in the "Deactivated users" tab.
Move it one level up, i.e. to the parent element of #admin-user-list
and #admin-deactivated-users-list.

Fixes #18928

[{'comment_id': 663245319, 'comment_body': "This should be called `heading_html`, if it's being interpolated into the DOM directly as HTML.

(Proper naming for this helps avoid security bugs).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 2, 21, 0, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 663328976, 'comment_body': 'There should be a minor provision bump as well since we are adding a dependency.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 3, 7, 4, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aryanshridhar', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677015129, 'comment_body': 'This commit makes too many scattered changes like this which need separate review.  You should pull the extraction of a `dialog_widget.close_modal()` function and migrating to it into preparatory commit series (or even a preparatory mini PR) to help manage the complexity of this migration.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 23, 42, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677015397, 'comment_body': "What's the story with removing the `fade` option?  

I think it's also worth extracting to a preparatory commit adding options like `disable_focus_yes_button` with an explanation for how you decided where it was needed; we ideally want the implementation change commit to not come with any changes to configuration.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 23, 43, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677015729, 'comment_body': "Similarly, if we can migrate from using a class to an ID for these submit buttons in a preparatory commit, that'd be helpful.

That said, doesn't this approach prevent us from rendering a modal on top of another modal?  I wonder if we want to stick with CSS classes rather than IDs here.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 23, 44, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677016034, 'comment_body': 'This would be great to make a preparatory commit that is just preserved when switching implementations.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 23, 44, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677016194, 'comment_body': "This is a great addition, and I'd also do as a preparatory commit before the cutover commit, because it's a commit that would work on top of master.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 26, 23, 45, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 678371708, 'comment_body': "This is intentionally placed after the migration commit since this doesn't apply to Bootstrap modals.

In Micromodal modals, we pass the common id (`dialog_widget_modal`) to the backdrop overlay and the extra id to the actual modal container, whereas in Bootstrap modals, we pass the common id to the container (the backdrop is separately placed in the DOM).
I could add an extra `div` just for this id, but that feels unnecessary.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 14, 43, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ganpa3', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 678373299, 'comment_body': "> That said, doesn't this approach prevent us from rendering a modal on top of another modal? I wonder if we want to stick with CSS classes rather than IDs here.

Modals on modals feel like a bad design nor do we have a use case for it yet :)
We also [check](https://github.com/zulip/zulip/blob/63ed398c22952387c1b89af7f9a6dcbc75c2cdfa/static/js/overlays.js#L128) for an active modal before opening another and raise an error if so.

Anyway, I went with classes here.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 14, 45, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ganpa3', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 678384905, 'comment_body': '> What's the story with removing the fade option?

Consistency.
A user wouldn't differentiate between a "normal" modal and a "settings" modal. If one shows up instantly, one would expect all the others to do the same. The difference between Bootstrap `fade` and non-`fade` is pretty noticeable (300 ms for fading).
Besides, I am not aware of any app that does this.

In the case of Micromodal, I have set 120 ms for in and 75 ms for out, so it wouldn't feel slow.

> I think it's also worth extracting to a preparatory commit adding options like disable_focus_yes_button with an explanation for how you decided where it was needed; we ideally want the implementation change commit to not come with any changes to configuration.

That was an experiment. I forgot to remove it.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 28, 14, 57, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ganpa3', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 678646687, 'comment_body': "Yeah, agreed. pr_title: tornado: Upgrade to the latest version.
pr_body:
1) `IOLoop.instance()` is replaced with `IOLoop.current()`
2) `self.finish()` is required only in functions decorated with
   `@web.asynchronous`.
3) `ioloop.PeriodicCallback` removed the `io_loop` parameter. asyncio's
   loop is used by default.
4) `gen.engine` and `web.asynchronous` are deprecated and removed.
   Use native async instead.
pr_review_comments: [{'comment_id': 664118391, 'comment_body': '`PROVISION_VERSION` in `version.py` will need a major bump for this incompatible upgrade.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 5, 20, 34, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'andersk', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 667265642, 'comment_body': 'This should wrap `super().select(timeout)` instead of copy-pasting its code.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 10, 0, 42, 11, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'andersk', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: node_tests: Run tests parallelly.
pr_body:
Fixes #9471

Without parallel:
```sh
$ time ./tools/test-js-with-node
real	0m18.278s
user	0m20.544s
sys	0m0.715s
```

With parallel:
```sh
$ time ./tools/test-js-with-node
real	0m13.127s
user	0m44.933s
sys	0m1.948s
```
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 683442862, 'comment_body': 'I would also add something like "Running in serial mode" at the end of that statement.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 5, 13, 17, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adnrs96', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 683450442, 'comment_body': 'I believe you can refactor this to avoid fiddling with existing code and creating double nested if construct over here.

I can just have the
```
if parallel > 1:
    dosomething
    return ret
```

Above the existing code you deleted. This way you do different op for parellel task and exit early or you can keep executing the non parellel route. This will restore the big nested part in the else statement to its original state.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 5, 13, 25, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'adnrs96', 'type': 'User'}]
